Subject: scan EVDI device indices 0..63, not 0..15

User had EVDI device IDs accumulate past 16 (`/dev/dri/card16`) after
several apollo restart cycles. `find_available_evdi_device()`'s loop
only checked `i < 16`, so the freshly-created EVDI card was invisible
to apollo. apollo logged:

  [VDISPLAY] Added EVDI device but no slot reported AVAILABLE after 2.5s

and fell back to passthrough mode — capturing the physical monitor
instead of the virtual display. From moonlight's side this looked like
"the Gamescope app shows a mirror of my main monitor".

Root cause: the kernel doesn't aggressively recycle DRM minor numbers.
When older EVDI cards aren't fully cleaned up (e.g. after a SIGKILL on
apollo, or after several create/destroy cycles), the next minor lands
at 16, 17, ... Apollo's old hardcoded limit of 16 was an arbitrary
choice — the search itself is just `evdi_check_device(i)`, a near-zero
sysfs stat. Raising the limit to 64 covers every realistic accumulation
without measurable cost.

Diagnostic message now also tells you which indices were searched, so
if this somehow trips again the user immediately sees what apollo
looked at.

--- a/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
@@ -752,9 +752,20 @@
     return 0;
   }

+  // Patch 0022: the EVDI device's DRM minor (i.e. /dev/dri/cardN's N) is NOT
+  // recycled by the kernel — each new `evdi_add_device()` reuses or bumps the
+  // next-free minor. If apollo has restarted after a previous crash that left
+  // a high-numbered card lingering, OR if other DRM devices (USB GPUs, etc.)
+  // have nudged the numbering up, the next EVDI card can land at minor 16+.
+  // The original loop only checked `i < 16`, so the new EVDI was invisible to
+  // apollo and we fell back to passthrough (= physical-monitor mirror).
+  // Bump the search range generously — `evdi_check_device()` is just a
+  // sysfs stat, near-zero cost.
+  static constexpr int EVDI_MAX_SEARCH = 64;
+
   static int find_available_evdi_device() {
     // First pass: any already-AVAILABLE EVDI device?
-    for (int i = 0; i < 16; i++) {
+    for (int i = 0; i < EVDI_MAX_SEARCH; i++) {
       if (evdi.check_device(i) == EVDI_AVAILABLE) {
         return i;
       }
@@ -770,7 +781,7 @@
     }
     BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY] Added EVDI device; scanning for new index...";
     for (int retry = 0; retry < 50; retry++) {
-      for (int i = 0; i < 16; i++) {
+      for (int i = 0; i < EVDI_MAX_SEARCH; i++) {
         if (evdi.check_device(i) == EVDI_AVAILABLE) {
           BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY] New EVDI device available at index " << i;
           return i;
@@ -778,7 +789,8 @@
       }
       usleep(50000);
     }
-    BOOST_LOG(warning) << "[VDISPLAY] Added EVDI device but no slot reported AVAILABLE after 2.5s";
+    BOOST_LOG(warning) << "[VDISPLAY] Added EVDI device but no slot reported AVAILABLE after 2.5s "
+                       << "(searched indices 0.." << (EVDI_MAX_SEARCH - 1) << ")";
     return -1;
   }

